.TH NODEUPDOWN.CONF 5 "November 2003" "LLNL" "LIBNODEUPDOWN"
.SH NAME
nodeupdown.conf \- specify alternate default values for the nodeupdown
                   library
.SH DESCRIPTION

Through a configuration file, system administrators may override the
statically configured default values in the 
.BR nodeupdown_load_data(3)
API function.  Overriding the statically configured default values
allows tools such as 
.BR whatsup(1)
to work without using the --hostname or --port options on the command line.

By default, the configuration file is stored at @NODEUPDOWN_CONF_FILE@.

.SH CONFIGURATION OPTIONS
The following are a list of configuration options that can be
specified in the configuration file.  Each configuration option must
be listed on a separate line.  Arguments for an option are separated
by any amount of whitespace.  Multiple arguments are also separated by
whitespace.  Comments can be marked by using the pound sign ("#")
character, and lines can be continued on the next using backslash
("\\").

.TP
.I hostnames host1 host2 host3 ...
Specify the hostname of the server to reach.  Multiple hostnames can
be listed up to a maximum of 8.
.TP
.I port num
Specify the port.
.TP
.I timeout_len seconds
Specify the timeout length in seconds.
.TP
.I masterlist_module ( name | filename | path)
Specify the masterlist module to use.  Masterlist modules are
first searched for in the nodeupdown package library, 
@NODEUPDOWN_MODULE_DIR@.  They are then searched for in the
current directory.

The following masterlist modules are available by default:

.if @MANPAGE_GENDERSLLNL@ \{
gendersllnl
  
\}
  
.if @MANPAGE_GENDERS@ \{
genders
  
\}
  
hostsfile
  
none
.TP
.I masterlist_module_options str
Specify arguments to pass to the masterlist module.  The arguments
are typically passed as key=value pairs.

The following parse options are currently supported by the default
masterlist modules:

.if @MANPAGE_GENDERSLLNL@ \{
gendersllnl: filename=<file> - Specify the path to the genders database.
  
\}
  
.if @MANPAGE_GENDERS@ \{
genders: filename=<file> - Specify the path to the genders database.
  
\}
  
hostsfile: filename=<file> - Specify the path to the hostsfile database.

.br
.SH FILES
@NODEUPDOWN_CONF_FILE@
.SH SEE ALSO
whatsup(1), libnodeupdown(3), nodeupdown_load_data(3)
